            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Riley was born and raised in a blue-collar family in the East Bay. His father worked in a shipbuilding yard, and his mother was a homemaker. Growing up, David saw firsthand the value of hard work and practical skills. He wasn't academically inclined in high school, preferring shop classes and figuring out how things worked.\n\nAfter high school, sensing the decline in traditional manufacturing, David enrolled in a community college and earned an Associate's Degree in Manufacturing Technology. This provided him with a blend of theoretical knowledge and practical application. His first job was as a line technician in a small electronics assembly plant in the South Bay. He quickly proved himself reliable and adept at problem-solving on the factory floor.\n\nA turning point came in his early thirties when he was promoted to a supervisory role. This required him to develop leadership skills and manage people, initially a challenge for the more introverted David. However, he found satisfaction in optimizing production processes and mentoring younger workers. He moved to San Francisco in his late twenties, drawn by the city's energy and proximity to a broader range of manufacturing opportunities as he climbed the ranks. He settled in a quiet pocket of the Outer Sunset, appreciating the neighborhood's down-to-earth feel and relative affordability compared to other parts of the city.\n\nDavid has been married to Sarah, a marketing professional, for fifteen years. They met through mutual friends and share a comfortable, no-frills life. While they don't have children, they are close to David's sister's family who live in the East Bay. His social connections are relatively small, centered around work colleagues, Sarah\u2019s friends, and occasional gatherings with his extended family.\n\nHis daily routine is predictable: an early start, the 9.5-mile drive across the bridge, a long day overseeing production, and a quiet evening at home. He enjoys tinkering with things around the house and following local sports teams.\n\nDavid\u2019s hopes and dreams are modest but deeply felt. He aspires to become a plant manager one day, a goal that represents both professional achievement and financial security. He also dreams of owning a small cabin up in the mountains for weekend getaways, a place to escape the urban bustle. San Francisco, with its mix of industry and natural beauty, provides the backdrop for his current life. He appreciates the city\u2019s diversity but finds solace in the familiar routines of his work and neighborhood, a steady presence in a constantly evolving landscape."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. The screech of the train brakes against the screech of seagulls. David, fresh off the plane, felt utterly alone walking out of CalTrain station. He gripped his worn duffel bag, the San Francisco air cool and unfamiliar. A wave of homesickness hit him, but then he saw the Bay Bridge spanning the water, a concrete testament to the kind of things he understood. It was scary, but also a thrilling challenge \u2013 proof he could make it on his own.\n\n2.  Meeting Sarah at that noisy crowded bar near Union Square. He almost didn\u2019t go. She was laughing, bright and easy while he stood awkwardly by the edge. She looked at him directly, no pretense. In that moment, something shifted. It wasn\u2019t about figuring things out or fixing something; it was about genuine connection. He felt seen, truly seen, for the first time in a long time.\n\n3. The first time a line he helped optimize went defect-free for an entire shift. It was late, and he was tired, but seeing those perfectly stacked units rolling off the line filled him with a quiet triumph. It wasn't a grand accomplishment to most, but for David, it was tangible proof that his practical skills and attention to detail truly mattered. This fueled his ambition, reminding him that hard work yielded real results.\n\n4. Driving his beat-up truck the Golden Gate Bridge for the first time after moving to the city. The fog was rolling in, obscuring the tops of the towers, making them seem infinite. He felt a sense of awe, the scale of it humbling and inspiring simultaneously. It solidified his feeling of being part of something bigger, a feeling he hadn't gotten from the flat expanse of the East Bay.\n\n5.  Sitting on the cold sand of Ocean Beach one rare, clear evening, watching the sun dip below the horizon, painting the sky in impossible colors. He wasn't thinking about work or bills, just the rhythm of the waves and the vastness of the Pacific. It was a profound sense of peace, a stark contrast to the controlled environment of the factory floor, reminding him of the simple beauty in the natural world."
